WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.910
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.333 --> 00:00:07.750
SPEAKER: Thank you so much for
joining us today, Michelle.

00:00:07.750 --> 00:00:07.948
MICHELLE LEE: Of course.

00:00:07.948 --> 00:00:09.740
Thank you for having me.

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:11.890
SPEAKER: So what is it
like to be editor-in-chief

00:00:11.890 --> 00:00:12.910
at "Allure" magazine?

00:00:12.910 --> 00:00:16.059
MICHELLE LEE: Oh,
what a question.

00:00:16.059 --> 00:00:18.340
So I always think of it
as-- so I've been working

00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:20.540
in media for the past 25 years.

00:00:20.540 --> 00:00:23.560
And when I first started out,
the role of the editor-in-chief

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:25.350
was completely different.

00:00:25.350 --> 00:00:27.850
So my first role here in New
York was actually at "Glamour."

00:00:27.850 --> 00:00:30.100
And so at the time, it
was "Glamour" magazine.

00:00:30.100 --> 00:00:32.710
The editor-in-chief was this
totally legendary editor

00:00:32.710 --> 00:00:34.030
named Ruth Whitney.

00:00:34.030 --> 00:00:36.220
And so she had that
one role though,

00:00:36.220 --> 00:00:38.500
which was to be the
editor-in-chief of a magazine.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:41.620
I think today being an
editor-in-chief is almost

00:00:41.620 --> 00:00:43.970
being the shepherd of a brand.

00:00:43.970 --> 00:00:46.250
So I've been there now
for about 3 and 1/2 years.

00:00:46.250 --> 00:00:48.190
And when I started,
I was very much

00:00:48.190 --> 00:00:50.860
seen as this new realm
of editor-in-chief who

00:00:50.860 --> 00:00:53.500
was sort of like the modern
editor who understood print,

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:55.270
and digital, and
video, and social,

00:00:55.270 --> 00:00:57.110
and all those different things.

00:00:57.110 --> 00:00:58.660
So one of my
biggest things to do

00:00:58.660 --> 00:01:01.780
was to have everybody understand
that we're not just a magazine

00:01:01.780 --> 00:01:02.680
anymore.

00:01:02.680 --> 00:01:04.475
So I remember when
I first started,

00:01:04.475 --> 00:01:06.100
people would still
introduce themselves

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:07.480
and say, I'm so-and-so.

00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:09.640
I'm an editor at
"Allure" magazine.

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:11.830
So we very much, like, that
first week, we're like,

00:01:11.830 --> 00:01:13.690
you're not an editor
at "Allure" magazine,

00:01:13.690 --> 00:01:15.560
you're an editor at "Allure."

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:17.920
And it was shifting the
viewpoint of everyone

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:19.720
internally, but also
externally to have

00:01:19.720 --> 00:01:21.920
them understand we're
not just a magazine,

00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:23.660
we're now a media brand.

00:01:23.660 --> 00:01:25.037
So flash forward
3 and 1/2 years,

00:01:25.037 --> 00:01:26.620
and I actually see
it much differently

00:01:26.620 --> 00:01:30.072
now where we're not just a media
brand, but we're also a brand.

00:01:30.072 --> 00:01:31.780
So we were talking
before we came up here

00:01:31.780 --> 00:01:35.560
about one of our businesses
is the "Allure" Beauty Box.

00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:37.540
So we now are in
consumer products.

00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:38.470
We're doing events.

00:01:38.470 --> 00:01:40.900
We're doing all those
other media things as well.

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:43.503
But I think that what's been
really innovative in the past 3

00:01:43.503 --> 00:01:44.920
and 1/2 years that
I've been there

00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:47.650
has been us shifting
from being just media

00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:49.745
into being an overall brand.

00:01:49.745 --> 00:01:52.120
So yes, but to answer your
question also about what is it

00:01:52.120 --> 00:01:55.070
like to be the editor-in-chief,
on social media

00:01:55.070 --> 00:01:58.130
if anyone follows me, we play
with a lot of beauty products.

00:01:58.130 --> 00:02:01.080
Like it's definitely
a very, very fun job.

00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:03.440
I have a couple of my
coworkers here who--

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:05.980
it's probably one of the only
offices that you can walk into

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:08.320
and it's completely
normal to walk by someone

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:10.840
and they're putting on
a full face of makeup.

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:13.930
We actually are testing for our
"Allure" Best of Beauty Awards

00:02:13.930 --> 00:02:14.900
right now.

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:19.150
And so every season, we test
10,000 products just for that.

00:02:19.150 --> 00:02:22.120
So it sounds so fun
and it is very fun,

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:24.430
but it's also
incredibly overwhelming

00:02:24.430 --> 00:02:27.130
because we go home every
single day with just bags

00:02:27.130 --> 00:02:28.600
and bags of stuff.

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:29.928
So that's the fun part of it.

00:02:29.928 --> 00:02:31.720
Like, I think playing
with beauty products,

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:34.870
getting to understand everything
about the beauty industry.

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:38.630
But I think being an editor in
chief, also, is a lot of work.

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:41.470
I think a lot of
times, people in media

00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:43.300
and in movies and
stuff have this picture

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:46.427
of what an editor in chief does.

00:02:46.427 --> 00:02:48.260
For example, "The Devil
Wears Prada," right?

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:50.710
I think that we all have this
image of what the Miranda

00:02:50.710 --> 00:02:52.485
Priestly character does.

00:02:52.485 --> 00:02:54.610
I always describe being an
editor in chief, though,

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:57.150
sort of like being the
director of a movie.

00:02:57.150 --> 00:02:59.650
For some of my family members,
for example, who don't really

00:02:59.650 --> 00:03:03.250
understand what an editor is,
I often got the question, like,

00:03:03.250 --> 00:03:04.420
what does an editor do?

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:06.880
Are you fixing the commas
and periods all the time?

00:03:06.880 --> 00:03:08.950
I'm like, that's a part
of it, but really, it's

00:03:08.950 --> 00:03:11.260
being the director
of a movie, where

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:13.930
I am the key
decision maker in all

00:03:13.930 --> 00:03:15.620
the different creative choices.

00:03:15.620 --> 00:03:18.190
So if we also wanted to get
into some new business--

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:20.590
if we wanted to launch a
line of brushes or makeup

00:03:20.590 --> 00:03:22.420
bags or anything
else, I would be

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:25.690
involved in the entire
creative process of it, too.

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:27.940
So I think that my role now--

00:03:27.940 --> 00:03:30.580
honestly, it touches a lot
more on the business side

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:33.460
than I ever could have
imagined 20 years ago.

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:34.750
SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:36.610
Well this next
question comes more

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:38.320
from a personal spot for me.

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:40.120
The publishing
industry in general

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:41.170
is overwhelmingly white.

00:03:41.170 --> 00:03:43.970
We're talking about novels,
magazines, et cetera.

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:45.730
And growing up as a
young girl, I rarely

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:47.700
saw models looking like
myself when I was--

00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:49.200
MICHELLE LEE: Where
did you grow up?

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:50.720
SPEAKER: In Canada,
in Vancouver.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:54.040
So when I was there, I never
saw a lot of cover models

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:57.100
who looked like me or who
were different on covers.

00:03:57.100 --> 00:04:00.670
And so this year alone,
in 2019, Serena Williams

00:04:00.670 --> 00:04:01.720
was your January cover.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:04.480
Then you had "Crazy Rich
Asians" star Gemma Chan

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:05.240
in another cover.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:09.710
So how do you approach
diversity at the organization,

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:11.710
and then how do you also
make that trickle down,

00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:13.063
beyond just editor in chief?

00:04:13.063 --> 00:04:15.730
MICHELLE LEE: Yeah, well I think
it's a couple different things.

00:04:15.730 --> 00:04:18.880
Part of it is, internally,
how we look at our staff,

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:20.890
how we look at
hiring, and I actually

00:04:20.890 --> 00:04:23.510
do think that that's very much
related to the type of content,

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:25.820
then, that we produce, also.

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:28.240
So in the 3 and 1/2 years
that I've been at "Allure"--

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:30.780
so right before I started,
I created a presentation

00:04:30.780 --> 00:04:32.530
for my bosses to say,
this is what I would

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:34.030
want to do with the brand.

00:04:34.030 --> 00:04:36.400
And obviously, you
start out having a plan,

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:37.850
and things evolve over time.

00:04:37.850 --> 00:04:40.060
I think if I looked back
at that presentation now,

00:04:40.060 --> 00:04:42.018
a lot of things would
have changed from it.

00:04:42.018 --> 00:04:44.560
But one of the things that was
core to that mission even back

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:46.370
then was diversity.

00:04:46.370 --> 00:04:48.290
So it's crazy actually
to think about

00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:51.940
that 3 and 1/2 years ago, there
was like hardly any diversity

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.100
when it came to
magazine covers, when

00:04:54.100 --> 00:04:56.650
it came to models on
runways, and actually, we've

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:59.290
come so far since then.

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:01.918
But I think back
three years ago,

00:05:01.918 --> 00:05:04.210
it was still considered to
be kind of a quote, unquote,

00:05:04.210 --> 00:05:07.598
"risk" to put a person
of color on the cover.

00:05:07.598 --> 00:05:09.140
I'd have to look
back at the numbers,

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:10.557
but I would guess
that on average,

00:05:10.557 --> 00:05:13.150
if you looked at the
normal magazine cover,

00:05:13.150 --> 00:05:16.630
it was maybe average to have
about two people of color

00:05:16.630 --> 00:05:18.670
on a cover in a year.

00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:22.570
Last year alone, I think
more than half of our covers

00:05:22.570 --> 00:05:24.610
were people of color.

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:27.190
But it's also not just doing
diversity for diversity's sake.

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:30.070
I think that now, we've moved
on to this space of looking

00:05:30.070 --> 00:05:33.100
at what it means as a story, but
also making sure that diversity

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:36.050
is just woven into
everything that we do

00:05:36.050 --> 00:05:37.840
and that it doesn't
feel heavy handed.

00:05:37.840 --> 00:05:39.965
I think that the thing that
we never want to happen

00:05:39.965 --> 00:05:42.070
is have someone feel
like it's exploitative

00:05:42.070 --> 00:05:45.970
or that we're just doing it
to get the pat on the back.

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:48.130
And also thinking about
what is diversity, right?

00:05:48.130 --> 00:05:50.770
I think that as an
Asian-American woman,

00:05:50.770 --> 00:05:53.410
I think of diversity
first and foremost

00:05:53.410 --> 00:05:57.380
from a gender perspective, but
also from race and ethnicity.

00:05:57.380 --> 00:05:59.050
But when it comes
to beauty, I think

00:05:59.050 --> 00:06:02.440
there are still a lot of
underserved communities

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:06.730
that deal with
body type, ageism.

00:06:06.730 --> 00:06:11.500
We, in 2017, famously banned the
term anti-aging from "Allure"

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:15.183
forever, and it actually became
just this global phenomenon

00:06:15.183 --> 00:06:17.350
where people around the
world were talking about it.

00:06:17.350 --> 00:06:20.080
I actually read
something that in the UK,

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:22.840
someone had put
forward a referendum

00:06:22.840 --> 00:06:26.620
to ban anti-aging from the UK
because they read our story.

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:28.325
So I feel like
there is something

00:06:28.325 --> 00:06:29.950
through diversity
and inclusion that we

00:06:29.950 --> 00:06:33.610
can do that's really important
and kind of beyond just making

00:06:33.610 --> 00:06:35.630
people feel good
about themselves.

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:36.720
I think that--

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:40.150
I have two kids, so for my
son and also my daughter,

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:41.410
I think it's really cool--

00:06:41.410 --> 00:06:42.910
the fact that they
can watch movies,

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:44.493
that they can look
at magazine covers,

00:06:44.493 --> 00:06:47.990
that they can look at photos
of people who look like them,

00:06:47.990 --> 00:06:50.560
and it's not necessarily that
this image of beauty that's

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:52.960
portrayed by the media or
pop culture or anything else

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:55.240
is just this one
super narrow view.

00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:57.460
So yeah, I think diversity--

00:06:57.460 --> 00:07:00.310
it's been very, very
important to me.

00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:01.810
We, last year, also--

00:07:01.810 --> 00:07:04.360
you mentioned the
Gemma Chan cover.

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:07.880
Last year for June,
we had our hair issue.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:10.672
So we were trying to think about
who we would have on the cover.

00:07:10.672 --> 00:07:12.130
So it's always this
big discussion.

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:13.810
We usually have
boards up and stuff

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:16.950
about looking at different
celebrities and models of who

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:18.760
is having a moment right now.

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:21.250
So we decided to choose
three Asian models,

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:23.980
and we-- it still was this
beautiful hair moment.

00:07:23.980 --> 00:07:26.230
We had one with
bright pink hair,

00:07:26.230 --> 00:07:29.320
we had one with black hair,
and one with platinum hair.

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:32.230
But putting three Asian
models on the cover--

00:07:32.230 --> 00:07:34.570
it was sort of this
statement without being too

00:07:34.570 --> 00:07:38.380
beat people over the head
of it about tokenism,

00:07:38.380 --> 00:07:41.320
because normally, if you look at
an advertisement or a magazine

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:43.630
cover where they talk
about it being diverse,

00:07:43.630 --> 00:07:47.380
there is usually, let's say,
five white models and then

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:48.730
one person of color.

00:07:48.730 --> 00:07:50.230
So for us, we were
like, we're going

00:07:50.230 --> 00:07:53.560
to give these three Asian
models their own cover.

00:07:53.560 --> 00:07:56.770
It went crazy out in the
world of social media.

00:07:56.770 --> 00:07:59.050
Chrissy Teigen tweeted
about it and stuff.

00:07:59.050 --> 00:08:01.330
And so I wrote my
editor's letter about--

00:08:01.330 --> 00:08:03.310
after we decided to
do that, I actually

00:08:03.310 --> 00:08:05.620
started looking into
how many Asian women had

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:08.560
been on the cover of "Allure"
in the past 28 years.

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:10.320
So in the past 28 years--

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:12.560
and I want to say it
was like 327 covers--

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:14.860
there had only been
two Asian women.

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:17.020
The first was Lucy
Liu over 10 years ago,

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:18.490
and then Olivia Munn.

00:08:18.490 --> 00:08:20.290
So in this one issue
of "Allure" where

00:08:20.290 --> 00:08:22.760
we had the three Asian
women on the cover,

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:24.730
we actually had more
Asian representation

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:27.320
than in the entire
28 year history.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:31.000
So that's just "Allure," and I
think for the entire industry,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.570
it's important for all
of us, when we can,

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:36.490
to be showing that these
things can be successful

00:08:36.490 --> 00:08:38.710
and showing that--

00:08:38.710 --> 00:08:40.448
just what it looks
like, because I

00:08:40.448 --> 00:08:42.490
think that the people who
are at the helm of some

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:43.720
of the other brands--

00:08:43.720 --> 00:08:46.880
they don't know what it is
until they actually see it.

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:49.660
And the thing that I
find kind of alarming--

00:08:49.660 --> 00:08:52.830
I talk a lot about diversity
in a lot of panels and stuff,

00:08:52.830 --> 00:08:54.580
and I think that there
are a lot of people

00:08:54.580 --> 00:08:56.560
who think that we're
good, that we're like,

00:08:56.560 --> 00:08:59.590
oh, the beauty and fashion
industry is so diverse now.

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:02.200
And I'm like, we
are so not there.

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:04.845
I think that people very
much still see it as like--

00:09:04.845 --> 00:09:06.220
they've got one
sort of-- they've

00:09:06.220 --> 00:09:07.720
got like a light
skinned black girl,

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:09.670
and then they go,
tick, like, ding.

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:11.710
We can click that off.

00:09:11.710 --> 00:09:14.260
And I just feel like
there's so much more to do

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:16.463
and so much more to
start the conversation.

00:09:16.463 --> 00:09:18.130
SPEAKER: Thank you
for providing a voice

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:21.470
to a lot of communities that
haven't seen representation.

00:09:21.470 --> 00:09:22.750
So I really appreciate that.

00:09:22.750 --> 00:09:23.810
MICHELLE LEE: Thank you.

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:27.602
SPEAKER: Beyond just disrupting
covers and narratives

00:09:27.602 --> 00:09:29.560
that you tell in "Allure,"
I'm curious to know,

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:32.020
from your POV, what
are some areas that

00:09:32.020 --> 00:09:35.290
are ripe for disruption in
the beauty industry today?

00:09:35.290 --> 00:09:36.610
MICHELLE LEE: So many.

00:09:36.610 --> 00:09:38.860
How many of you work in the
beauty industry right now?

00:09:38.860 --> 00:09:40.777
Because I feel like there
were some of you who

00:09:40.777 --> 00:09:41.910
had beauty clients, right?

00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:42.430
OK.

00:09:42.430 --> 00:09:44.740
So beauty is so
exciting right now.

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:47.590
I don't have to tell
you guys who work in it.

00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:51.265
I do think, though, in the
world of sustainability,

00:09:51.265 --> 00:09:53.890
I actually think that there's a
lot of interesting conversation

00:09:53.890 --> 00:09:57.070
happening right now, and
partly because if you think

00:09:57.070 --> 00:10:01.030
about beauty and personal
care, how much waste there is,

00:10:01.030 --> 00:10:03.150
not only just on the
consumer portion of things.

00:10:03.150 --> 00:10:04.650
Like we talk about
this all the time

00:10:04.650 --> 00:10:08.640
because us testing 10,000
products in a three month

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:11.070
period for Best of Beauty--
imagine how much just

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:12.628
packaging waste we get.

00:10:12.628 --> 00:10:15.170
And it tends to be that the more
expensive brands, let's say,

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:16.260
in skin care--

00:10:16.260 --> 00:10:18.270
we always equate it to
like a Russian doll where

00:10:18.270 --> 00:10:20.110
it's like you get this
little tiny cream,

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:21.820
but it's inside 10
boxes that you have

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:24.010
to kind of open up like this.

00:10:24.010 --> 00:10:26.160
There's a lot of waste
within that process,

